  "prompt": "Is it OK to put two different GPUs in the same system?",
  "response": "In most cases, it is possible to use two different GPUs in the same system, but there are some important considerations:\n\n1. For Gaming/General Use:\n- Different GPU models can often coexist, but they may not work together for graphics tasks\n- You'll typically use one GPU as the primary display adapter\n- Performance optimization can be challenging\n\n2. For Professional/Workstation Use:\n- Some professional applications support multi-GPU configurations\n- Matching GPU architectures is often recommended\n- CUDA or OpenCL compatibility matters\n\n3. Technical Requirements:\n- Motherboard must have multiple PCIe slots\n- Sufficient power supply\n- Compatible driver support\n- Similar PCIe generations preferred\n\n4. Common Scenarios:\n- One GPU for gaming, another for compute/rendering\n- Different GPUs for multi-monitor setups\n- Using integrated + dedicated graphics\n\n5. Potential Limitations:\n- Performance may not scale linearly\n- Potential driver/compatibility issues\n- Increased power consumption\n\n6. Best Practices:\n- Check manufacturer compatibility\n- Ensure adequate cooling\n- Update graphics drivers\n- Verify system power capabilities\n\nRecommendation: Consult your specific hardware and software requirements before mixing GPUs.",
